  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         [P]         \colon  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (B_{\bullet  G})         \to  \operatorname {H}^\bullet ([P/G]_\bullet )         \xleftarrow [(6.1.2.2)]{\sim } \operatorname {H}^\bullet (S).       \tag{6.1.3.1}       ]]></fr:tex>
  </fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:backmatter>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Context">Context</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2284</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>6.1.3</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^t]]></fr:tex> be the topological space consisting of a single point.
    We define the <fr:em>simplicial classifying space</fr:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>, denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B_{\bullet  G}]]></fr:tex>, to be the simplicial space
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       B_{\bullet  G}       = [P^t/G]_\bullet .     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> be a principal homogeneous space for the group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
    The evident morphism
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {cosq}(P\to  S)       = [P/G]_\bullet        \to  [P^t/G]_\bullet        = B_{\bullet  G}     ]]></fr:tex>
    defines a composite morphism

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2259</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>6.1.3.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         [P]         \colon  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (B_{\bullet  G})         \to  \operatorname {H}^\bullet ([P/G]_\bullet )         \xleftarrow [(6.1.2.2)]{\sim } \operatorname {H}^\bullet (S).       \tag{6.1.3.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
            <fr:p>We will see below that, in good cases, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (B_{\bullet  G})=\operatorname {H}^\bullet (B_G)]]></fr:tex>, and that the image of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[P]]]></fr:tex> consists of the <fr:em>characteristic classes</fr:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Backlinks">Backlinks</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2285</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.1.4</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.1.4.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>6.1.4</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> be a Lie group, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B_G]]></fr:tex> a classifying space for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  U_G\to  B_G]]></fr:tex> the universal principal homogeneous <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>-space.
    Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>-space;
    then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X\times  U_G]]></fr:tex> is a principal homogeneous <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>-space over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X\times  U_G/G]]></fr:tex> such that, for every equivariant sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {pr}_1^*F]]></fr:tex> is the inverse image of a sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^G]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X\times  U_G/G]]></fr:tex>.
    Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_G]]></fr:tex> is contractible, and by <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="6.1.2.2" />, we have

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2261</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.1.4.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.1.4.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>6.1.4.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,G;F)         \xrightarrow {\sim } \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X\times  U_G,G;\operatorname {pr}_1^*F)         \xleftarrow {\sim } \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X\times  U_G/G,F^G).       \tag{6.1.4.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
            <fr:p>In particular, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X=P^t]]></fr:tex>,

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2262</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.1.4.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.1.4.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>6.1.4.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {H}^\bullet (B_{\bullet  G})         = \operatorname {H}^\bullet (B_G).       \tag{6.1.4.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
            <fr:p>We can see that the isomorphism in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.4.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.4.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="6.1.4.2" /> is a particular case of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="6.1.3.1" /> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S=B_G]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P=U_G]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2286</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-9.1.2</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-9.1.2.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>9.1.2</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> be an algebraic group (over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>), and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> a (algebraic) principal homogeneous space of group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> over a scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.
    Then the morphism
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       [P]\colon \operatorname {H}^\bullet (\mathrm {B}_G)=\operatorname {H}^\bullet (\mathrm {B}_{\bullet  G})       \to  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X)     ]]></fr:tex>
    is a morphism of mixed Hodge structures.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2287</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#244</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-244.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>This follows from the definition (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.1.3.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="6.1.3.1" />) of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[P]]]></fr:tex> and from functoriality (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.3.4" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.3.4.xml" taxon="Definition" number="8.3.4" />).</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
